summaries.title: Summary 300.1
summaries.summaryText: Aaliyah recounted repeated experiences of having her technical input questioned in group settings. She also described taking on emotional labor to support other students facing similar bias. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Summary 300.2
summaries.summaryText: Daniel expressed pride in representing his family’s aspirations but also noted ongoing struggles with imposter syndrome. He values belonging through peer groups that normalize his experiences as a first-gen student of color in STEM. [Part 1/4]

timelinePoints.eventDescription: Faced academic probation warning after struggling with Calculus II due to lack of tutoring access. [Timeline 4]
Presented a project on sustainable energy systems at an undergraduate research showcase. [Timeline 3]
Joined the Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers during her first semester to find community and mentorship. [Timeline 1]
Presented a project on sustainable energy systems at an undergraduate research showcase. [Timeline 4]

themes.title: Intersection of Culture and Academic Identity
themes.description: Cultural expectations of excellence create dual pressure for first-gen students in technical majors. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Mentorship Networks as Retention Mechanisms
themes.description: Mentorship emerges as a consistent strategy for increasing belonging and persistence for students from marginalized groups. Aaliyah’s mentorship program demonstrates how peer-led initiatives can fill institutional gaps. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Imposter Syndrome Among First-Generation Asian-American Students
themes.description: Daniel’s experience illustrates how first-generation students often internalize academic challenges as personal shortcomings, especially when they lack peers with shared backgrounds in STEM programs. [Extended 3]

themes.title: First-Generation Adaptation to STEM Rigor
themes.description: Luis’s story demonstrates resilience through peer and cultural support. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Sense of Belonging in STEM for Students of Color
themes.description: Maria’s reflections highlight how peer representation and visibility in classrooms significantly influence belonging and persistence for Latina women in engineering. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Navigating Institutional Barriers as a First-Generation Student
themes.description: First-generation identity shapes how Maria interprets bureaucratic and academic systems, creating additional cognitive and emotional labor compared to continuing-generation peers. [Extended 3]

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I feel like everyone else just gets it — like I’m pretending to belong in these classes. [Context 2]
When our robotics team included people from different majors, the solutions got way more creative. It wasn’t just engineers thinking like engineers. [Context 3]
I love leading projects, but it’s exhausting always being the one to explain why diversity matters in engineering teams. [Context 2]
It took me a year to realize struggling is normal — not a sign that I’m not supposed to be here. [Context 4]
Having mentors who also came from immigrant families helped me feel like my story belonged here too. [Context 3]
You can’t innovate if you’re burned out — STEM needs to start treating wellness as part of success. [Context 4]

areasForImprovement.title: Formal Recognition for Student Advocacy and Mentorship Work
areasForImprovement.description: Students like Aaliyah contribute substantial unpaid labor in mentoring and advocacy roles. Institutions should recognize these contributions as part of leadership and service learning frameworks. [Extended 4]

areasForImprovement.title: Integrate Wellness Programming into STEM Curriculum
areasForImprovement.description: Develop optional workshops or credit modules linking mental health and STEM performance. [Extended 2]
